Renderer and Basic Drawing

Introduction

In this section, you are going to learn how to create a plain window and draw some basic lines with the SDL 2.0 library.

To do so, you will draw two versions of a fractal canopy, which is a type of fractal tree. The first version will be static. That is, the properties of the canopy will be set at compile time (except for the size, because the window will be resizable). The second version will be dynamic: the properties of the canopy will change at runtime.

In this practical, some variables are pointers, but do not worry, you do not have to know what a pointer is to do or to understand this practical. For now, consider that pointers are just simple variables (and technically, they are). We will see them in details later on.

The Makefile

Makefile
# Makefile

CC = gcc
CPPFLAGS =
CFLAGS = -Wall -Wextra -O3 `pkg-config --cflags sdl2`
LDFLAGS =
LDLIBS = `pkg-config --libs sdl2` -lm

all: static dynamic

SRC = plain.c static.c dynamic.c
OBJ = ${SRC:.c=.o}
EXE = ${SRC:.c=}

plain: plain.o
static: static.o
dynamic: dynamic.o

.PHONY: clean

clean:
	${RM} ${OBJ}
	${RM} ${EXE}

# END

Plain Window

Introduction

The following code creates a plain window and draws two diagonals. Read it through to make sense of it.

plain.c
#include <err.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>

// Initial width and height of the window.
const int INIT_WIDTH = 640;
const int INIT_HEIGHT = 400;

// Draws two diagonals.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
void draw(SDL_Renderer* renderer)
{
    // Clears the renderer (sets the background to black).
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

    // Sets the color for drawing operations to white.
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 255, 255, 255, 255);

    // Draws the two diagonals.
    SDL_RenderDrawLine(renderer, 0, 0, INIT_WIDTH, INIT_HEIGHT);
    SDL_RenderDrawLine(renderer, 0, INIT_HEIGHT, INIT_WIDTH, 0);

    // Updates the display.
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
}

// Event loop that calls the relevant event handler.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
void event_loop(SDL_Renderer* renderer)
{
    // Draws the diagonals (first draw).
    draw(renderer);

    // Creates a variable to get the events.
    SDL_Event event;

    while (1)
    {
        // Waits for an event.
        SDL_WaitEvent(&event);

        switch (event.type)
        {
            // If the "quit" button is pushed, ends the event loop.
            case SDL_QUIT:
                return;
        }
    }
}

int main()
{
    // Initializes the SDL.
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) != 0)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Creates a window.
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Plain Window", 0, 0, INIT_WIDTH, INIT_HEIGHT,
            SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN | SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE);
    if (window == NULL)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Creates a renderer.
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (renderer == NULL)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Dispatches the events.
    event_loop(renderer);

    // Destroys the objects.
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}

Compile and execute this code with the following commands: 

$ make plain
gcc -Wall -Wextra -O3 `pkg-config --cflags sdl2`   -c -o plain.o plain.c
gcc   plain.o  `pkg-config --libs sdl2` -lm -o plain
$ ./plain

If you use i3, the window is automatically resized. In our example, this is unwanted. So, position the mouse cursor on the plain window and active the floating mode. You can toggle the floating mode for a window by pressing Mod+Shift+Space (see i3 - Floating).

Here is a screenshot of the expected result:

This program is divided into three parts.

  • The main function, which is the entry point of the program.
  • The event_loop() function, which dispatches events.
  • The draw() function, which draws the diagonals.

The Main Function

This function is also divided into three parts.

  • Initialization.
  • Execution of the event loop.
  • Memory release.

The first step is to initialize the SDL with the SLD_Init() function. In our case, we need to initialize the video subsystem only. Read the SDL documentation if you need to initialize other subsystems.

Note that if an error occurs, the function returns a value different from 0. In this practical, we will exit the program with an error message anytime an SDL function returns an error. To get more information about the error, we can call the SDL_GetError() function. So, we will exit the program by executing the following instruction: 

errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

The next step is to create a window. To do that, we can call SDL_CreateWindow(). We want the window to be shown and resizable. That is why we use the SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN and SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE flags.

In order to draw on the window, we also have to create a renderer. That is the purpose of the SDL_CreateRenderer() function. Read the documentation to find out what the SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED flag refers to.

When such initialization is done, we can execute the event_loop() function.

Then, when event_loop() returns, we can free the memory by destroying the renderer and the main window. Finally, the last step is to call the SDL_Quit() function, which cleans up all initialized subsystems.

The event_loop() Function

This function is the event loop of the program. It calls the relevant event handler. When the event loop comes to an end, the function must return so that the main function can exit properly.

Before waiting for an event, we first call the draw() function in order to display the diagonals when the window shows up on the screen.

Then, we wait for an event in an infinite loop. The SDL_WaitEvent() function waits indefinitely for the next available event. When such an event occurs, the function returns and some information about the event is held in the event variable. For example, the event.type field contains the type of the event. The different types are listed in the documentation of the SDL_Event structure.

In our case, only one event is handled: the SDL_QuitEvent event. When it occurs, the value of even.type is SDL_QUIT. This event is triggered when the window must be closed (e.g. when a user clicks on the close button or press Mod+Shift+q on i3). For the time being, we do not need an event handler to close the window. We just have to stop the event loop by returning from the function.

The draw() Function

This function draws the two diagonals. The drawing operations must be done by the renderer.

First, the background is set to black. The SDL_SetRenderDrawColor() sets the color used for drawing operations (it uses the RGBA color model), and the SDL_RenderClear function clears the rendering target with the current drawing color.

Then, the current drawing color is set to white and the two diagonals are drawn by calling SDL_RenderDrawLine().

Finally, we have to update the screen with the SDL_RenderPresent() function.

Note that even if most drawing functions return values for error handling, we just ignore such values because we do not need to exit the program if the drawing is not done properly. That way, we can avoid some useless boilerplate code.

Handling the Resized Event

Execute the previous program (and active the floating mode if you use i3). Now, resize the plain window by grabbing and moving the borders. As you can see, there are unwanted effects (note that on i3 such effects may not appear). Here is an example:

Such effects occur, because, so far, we have not handled the SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED event. So, when the window is resized, the renderer does not update the display.

Modify the event loop this way: 

// Event loop that calls the relevant event handler.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
void event_loop(SDL_Renderer* renderer)
{
    // Draws the diagonals (first draw).
    draw(renderer);

    // Creates a variable to get the events.
    SDL_Event event;

    while (1)
    {
        // Waits for an event.
        SDL_WaitEvent(&event);

        switch (event.type)
        {
            // If the "quit" button is pushed, ends the event loop.
            case SDL_QUIT:
                return;

            // If the window is resized, redraws the diagonals.
            case SDL_WINDOWEVENT:
                if (event.window.event == SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED)
                    draw(renderer);
                break;
        }
    }
}

Note that the SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED event is a sub-event of SDL_WindowEvent.

Recompile, execute the code, active the floating mode (i3 only) and enlarge the window. The unwanted effect has been removed but the lengths of the diagonals are not updated (the display may change on i3).

Here is a screenshot of the expected result:

Resizing Diagonals

We can get the current size of the window's area by calling either SDL_GetWindowSize() or SDL_GetRendererOutputSize(). However, in most cases these calls are useless because when the SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED event occurs, the following fields already contains the new size.

  • event.window.data1 contains the new width.
  • event.window.data2 contains the new height.

So, let us use these variables to update the lengths of the diagonals. Modify the plain.c file as follows (only the draw() and event_loop() functions have been modified).

plain.c
#include <err.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>

// Initial width and height of the window.
const int INIT_WIDTH = 640;
const int INIT_HEIGHT = 400;

// Draws two diagonals.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
// w: Current width of the window.
// h: Current height of the window.
void draw(SDL_Renderer* renderer, int w, int h)
{
    // Clears the renderer (sets the background to black).
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

    // Sets the color for drawing operations to white.
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 255, 255, 255, 255);

    // Draws the two diagonals.
    SDL_RenderDrawLine(renderer, 0, 0, w, h);
    SDL_RenderDrawLine(renderer, 0, h, w, 0);

    // Updates the display.
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
}

// Event loop that calls the relevant event handler.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
void event_loop(SDL_Renderer* renderer)
{
    // Width and height of the window.
    int w = INIT_WIDTH;
    int h = INIT_HEIGHT;

    // Draws the diagonals (first draw).
    draw(renderer, w, h);

    // Creates a variable to get the events.
    SDL_Event event;

    while (1)
    {
        // Waits for an event.
        SDL_WaitEvent(&event);

        switch (event.type)
        {
            // If the "quit" button is pushed, ends the event loop.
            case SDL_QUIT:
                return;

            // If the window is resized, updates and redraws the diagonals.
            case SDL_WINDOWEVENT:
                if (event.window.event == SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED)
                {
                    w = event.window.data1;
                    h = event.window.data2;
                    draw(renderer, w, h);
                }
                break;
        }
    }
}

int main()
{
    // Initializes the SDL.
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) != 0)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Creates a window.
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Plain Window", 0, 0, INIT_WIDTH, INIT_HEIGHT,
            SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN | SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE);
    if (window == NULL)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Creates a renderer.
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (renderer == NULL)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Dispatches the events.
    event_loop(renderer);

    // Destroys the objects.
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}

Recompile, execute the code and try again to enlarge the window. This time, the lengths of the diagonals are updated according to the size of the window. Here is a screenshot of the expected result:

The Static Fractal Canopy

In this section, you are going to keep the same structure as the previous program, but instead of drawing two resizable diagonals, you are going to draw a resizable fractal canopy.

The file to complete is as follows:

static.c
#include <err.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>

// Initial width and height of the window.
const int INIT_WIDTH = 640;
const int INIT_HEIGHT = 400;

// Ratio used to reduce the length of a segment.
const double RATIO = 0.7;

// Maximum recursion level.
const int TOP_LEVEL = 10;

// Step angle to rotate a segment.
const double STEP_ANGLE = M_PI / 6;

// Recursive function that draws the fractal canopy.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
// x: Abscissa of the starting point of the segments.
// y: Ordinate of the starting point of the segments.
// len: Length of the segments.
// a: Angle use to rotate the segments.
// level: Recursion level (0 = first iteration).
void v(SDL_Renderer* renderer, int x, int y, double len, double a, int level)
{
    // If level is 0, draws a single segment.
    if (level == 0)
    {
        // Gets the ordinate of the end of the segment.
        int y1 = y - len;

        // Draws the segment.
        SDL_RenderDrawLine(renderer, x, y, x, y1);

        // Draws the segments for the next level.
        v(renderer, x, y1, RATIO * len, 0, 1);
    }

    // Otherwise, draws all the other segments.
    else if (level <= TOP_LEVEL)
    {
        // TODO
    }
}

// Initializes the renderer, draws the fractal canopy and updates the display.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
// w: Current width of the window.
// h: Current height of the window.
void draw(SDL_Renderer* renderer, int w, int h)
{

    // If the width or the height is too small, we do not draw anything.
    if (w < 20 || h < 20)
        return;

    // Clears the renderer (sets the background to black).
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

    // Sets the color for drawing operations to white.
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 255, 255, 255, 255);

    // Draws the fractal canopy.
    v(renderer, w / 2, h, h / 4, 0, 0);

    // Updates the display.
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
}

// Event loop that calls the relevant event handler.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
void event_loop(SDL_Renderer* renderer)
{
    // Width and height of the window.
    int w = INIT_WIDTH;
    int h = INIT_HEIGHT;

    // Draws the fractal canopy (first draw).
    draw(renderer, w, h);

    // Creates a variable to get the events.
    SDL_Event event;

    while (1)
    {
        // Waits for an event.
        SDL_WaitEvent(&event);

        switch (event.type)
        {
            // If the "quit" button is pushed, ends the event loop.
            case SDL_QUIT:
                return;

            // If the window is resized, updates and redraws the diagonals.
            case SDL_WINDOWEVENT:
                if (event.window.event == SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED)
                {
                    w = event.window.data1;
                    h = event.window.data2;
                    draw(renderer, w, h);
                }
                break;
        }
    }
}

int main()
{
    // Initializes the SDL.
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) != 0)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Creates a window.
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Static Fractal Canopy", 0, 0, INIT_WIDTH, INIT_HEIGHT,
            SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN | SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE);
    if (window == NULL)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Creates a renderer.
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (renderer == NULL)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // Dispatches the events.
    event_loop(renderer);

    // Destroys the objects.
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}

The above program draws the trunk of the tree (the first segment). You are going to complete it in order to draw the full tree (all the segments).

The draw() function has been slightly modified. The two calls to SDL_RenderDrawLine() have been removed and replaced by the call to the v() function, which draws the fractal tree.

This function is recursive. The first level of iterations (level 0) draws the first segment (this part of the code is given). The other levels draw two smaller left- and right-angled segments.

Example with two iterations (level 1):

Example with three iterations (level 2):

We will say that:

  • Segment 1 is the left-angled segment of segment 0.
  • Segment 2 is the right-angled segment of segment 0.
  • Segment 3 is the left-angled segment of segment 1.
  • Segment 4 is the right-angled segment of segment 1.
  • Segment 5 is the left-angled segment of segment 2.
  • Segment 6 is the right-angled segment of segment 2.

Let us look at the prototype of v(): 

void v(SDL_Renderer* renderer, int x, int y, double len, double a, int level)

The first parameter is the renderer.

The x and y parameters give the position of the two segments that must be drawn (or the initial position of the first segment for level 0). In other words, it is the intersection of the two segments.

The len parameter is the length of the two segments.

The a parameter is the angle of rotation of the previous segment. The reference is the vertical axis.

For example:

  • For level 0, the angle is irrelevant (no previous segment).
  • For level 1, the angle must be 0 because the angle of segment 0 is 0.
  • For level 2, the angle must be:
    • (0 + step angle) when the previous segment is segment 1.
    • (0 - step angle) when the previous segment is segment 2.
  • For level 3, the angle must be:
    • (0 + step angle + step angle) when the previous segment is segment 3.
    • (0 + step angle - step angle) when the previous segment is segment 4.
    • (0 - step angle + step angle) when the previous segment is segment 5.
    • (0 - step angle - step angle) when the previous segment is segment 6.

The level parameter is the current level of iterations (it starts from 0).

Complete the missing part of the v() function.

Here are some tips:

Let us consider the following call: 

v(renderer, x, y, len, a, level);

Whatever the level value (except for 0), we can consider that we are in the following case:

The gray segment has been drawn in the previous iteration. Now, we want to draw the left- and right-angled segments of the gray segment. So, we have to determine the (x1, y1) and (x2, y2) pairs of coordinates in order to draw two lines: from (x, y) to (x1, y1) and from (x, y) to (x2, y2).

By applying basic trigonometric formulas, we can easily deduce that:

  • x1 = x - len * sin(a + step angle)
  • y1 = y - len * cos(a + step angle)

You can follow the following steps:

  • Work out the (x1, y1) coordinates for the left-angled segment. You can use the cos() and sin() functions from the standard library.
  • Work out the (x2, y2) coordinates for the right-angled segment.
  • Draw the left- and right-angled segments
  • Recursively call the v() function for the next level:
    • A first time for the left-angled segment.
    • A second time for the right-angled segment.

Finally:

  • Do not forget to reduce the length of the segments with the RATIO constant.
  • Note that the step angle and the maximum recursion level are stored in the STEP_ANGLE and TOP_LEVEL constants respectively.

The main function has not changed (except for the title).

The TOP_LEVEL and STEP_ANGLE constants have been removed because their values are now going to change at runtime. These values are passed as parameters to the v() function.

Rewrite the v() function. Just replace the constants by the variables (and obviously, update the recursive call to v()).

The draw() function takes two new parameters: mouse_x and mouse_y. They give the position of the mouse cursor and are used to determine the values of top_level and step_angle. Rewrite this function. Use the two following instructions to work out the values of top_level and step_angle. That way, top_level will vary from 0 to 10 and step_angle will vary from π/20 to π/2. 

int top_level = DIM(mouse_y / (h / 11), 0, 10);
double step_angle = DIM(M_PI / (2.0 + mouse_x / (w / 18.0)), M_PI / 20, M_PI / 2);

Finally, modify the event_loop() function in order to handle the SDL_MOUSEMOTION event. Update the values of the mouse_x and mouse_y local variables. To do so, use the event.motion.x and event.motion.y fields. Do not forget to update the display.

Makefile

The following Makefile is provided: 

# Makefile

CC = gcc
CPPFLAGS =

Displaying an Image

In this section, you are going to display an image.

Previously, we used the renderer to draw some lines. But with SDL, a renderer is not enough to display an image. There are different ways to manipulate images in SDL. We can use either textures or surfaces. When we do not need to manipulate images pixel by pixel, it is more efficient to use textures. Otherwise, it is more convenient to use surfaces. In this section, our purpose is just to display and resize an image. So, textures are the best choice. They are fast and they can resize images automatically.

Here is the code you have to complete:

display.c
#include <err.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL_image.h>

// Updates the display.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
// texture: Texture that contains the image.

    // TODO
}

// Event loop that calls the relevant event handler.
//
// renderer: Renderer to draw on.
// texture: Texture to display.
void event_loop(SDL_Renderer* renderer, SDL_Texture* texture)
{
    // TODO
}

int main(int argc, char** argv)
{
    // Checks the number of arguments.
    if (argc != 2)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "Usage: image-file");

    // TODO:
    // - Initialize the SDL.
    // - Create a window.
    // - Create a renderer.
    // - Create a texture from the image.

    // Gets the width and the height of the texture.
    int w, h;
    if (SDL_QueryTexture(texture, NULL, NULL, &w, &h) != 0)
        errx(EXIT_FAILURE, "%s", SDL_GetError());

    // TODO:
    // - Resize the window according to the size of the image.
    // - Dispatch the events.
    // - Destroy the objects.

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}

The Main Function

First, initialize the SDL and create a new window and a renderer (do not forget to exit with an error message if an error occurs). Do not worry about the size of the window (you are going to resize it later on).

Then you have to create a texture that contains the image. There are different ways to do it. First we can create a surface with SDL_LoadBMP() and then create a texture from this surface with SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(). But unfortunately, SDL_LoadBMP() supports the BMP format only.

Actually, you'd be better off calling IMG_LoadTexture() instead. This function supports different image formats and loads the image in the texture (we do not need to create a surface). However, this function is part of an additional library that extends SDL functionalities. Therefore, the SDL_Image 2.0 extension must be installed on your computer (note that it is already installed on the school's computers). Call this function and exit with an error message if it returns an error.

You can get the size of the texture (i.e. the size of the image) by calling SDL_QueryTexture(). Such code is given.

Now that you have the size of the image, you can resize the window by calling SDL_SetWindowSize().

Dispatch the event (i.e. call event_loop()).

Finally, destroy all the objects with the following functions: SDL_DestroyTexture(), SDL_DestroyRenderer(), SDL_DestroyWindow() and SDL_Quit().

They must be destroyed in the reverse order of their creation.

The even_loop() Function

This function is quite simple. It handles only two events: SDL_QUIT and SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED. When the window is resized, just call the draw() function.

The draw() Function

This function updates the display. First you have to copy the texture to the renderer. You can call the SDL_RenderCopy() function (you have to copy the entire texture into the entire renderer). Finally, call SDL_RenderPresent() to display the result.

Download the following image: image.png ; and execute the following commands to compile and test your code. 

$ make display
gcc -Wall -Wextra -O3 `pkg-config --cflags sdl2 SDL2_image`   -c -o display.o display.c
gcc   display.o  `pkg-config --libs sdl2 SDL2_image` -o display
$ ./display image.png

Note that when you resize the window, the image should resize automatically (this is because you use a texture to display the image).

Converting into Grayscale

Now that you can display an image, you are going to convert it into grayscale. The final behavior of your program must be as follows:

  • First, it displays the colored image.
  • Then, when any key is pressed, it displays the grayscale image.
  • Then, when any key is pressed, it displays the colored image.
  • Then, when any key is pressed, it displays the grayscale image.
  • Then, when any key is pressed, it displays the colored image.
  • And so on...

Here is the file to complete:

The main Function

To convert the image into grayscale, you have to modify it pixel by pixel. As said previously, it will be more convenient to use a surface. However, you will also use a texture in order to display and resize the image. In fact, you will use one surface and two textures:

  • One surface to convert the image.
  • One texture to display the colored image.
  • One texture to display the grayscale image.

The principle is quite simple.

  • Create a surface from a colored image. You just have to call the load_image() function.
  • Resize the window according to the size of the image. You can get that size with the w and h fields of the SDL_Surface structure. For instance, if s is of type SDL_Surface*:
    • s->w gives the width in pixels.
    • s->h gives the height in pixels.
    You do not have to call SDL_QueryTexture().
  • Create a texture from the colored surface. You can call SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface().
  • Convert the surface into grayscale. Just call the surface_to_grayscale() function.
  • Create a new texture from the grayscale surface. You can still call SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface().
  • The surface is now useless. You can free it. Just call SDL_FreeSurface().
  • Dispatch the events.
  • Destroy the objects.

The draw() Function

This function is the same as in the previous section.

The event_loop() Function

This function handles three events:

  • SDL_QUIT
  • SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED
  • SDL_KEYDOWN

The first two events must be handled as previously.

The SDL_KEYDOWN event occurs when a key is pressed. Look at the given code in this function. A t variable is initialized with the colored texture. Each time the image must be displayed, you have to call the draw() function with t as the second parameter. Then, when a key is pressed, you have to switch the value of t from the colored texture to the grayscale texture ; and vice versa any time a key is pressed.

The load_image() Function

This function loads an image into a surface and returns it. To do so, you have to use the IMG_Load() function from the SLD_image 2.0 extension.

But you have to know that there are different ways to encode the pixels in a surface. As you are going to modify them, you must choose a specific format. You will use the RGB color model. The problem is that when you use IMG_Load(), you cannot choose the format used to create the surface.

Therefore, you have to create a new surface from the surface returned by IMG_Load(). When you create this new surface, you can specify the format you want. Just call SDL_ConvertSurfaceFormat() with SDL_PIXELFORMAT_RGB888 as a second argument and 0 as a third argument.

So, your function must:

  • Load the image into a temporary surface.
  • Create a new surface in the desired format.
  • Free the temporary surface.
  • Return the surface in the desired format.

This function must exit with an error message if any error occurs.

The pixel_to_grayscale() Function

This function converts a color into grayscale. The color is stored in a 32-bit word, which contains the RGB values.

To get the RGB values of a color in the r, g, b variables, you can use the following instructions: 

Uint8 r, g, b;
SDL_GetRGB(pixel_color, format, &r, &g, &b);

To get a 32-bit word from RGB values, you can use the following instruction: 

Uint32 color = SDL_MapRGB(format, r, g, b);

To convert a color into grayscale, you have to compute the weighted average of the RGB values:

average = 0.3*r + 0.59*g + 0.11*b

Then, you have to update the RGB values by using this average (r = g = b = average).

The surface_to_grayscale() Function

This function converts all the pixels in a surface to grayscale.

To get an array of pixels, you can use the following instruction: 

Uint32* pixels = surface->pixels;

To get the total number of pixels (the length of the array), you can use the following instruction: 

int len = surface->w * surface->h;

To get the format of the surface, you can use the following instruction: 

SDL_PixelFormat* format = surface->format;

Each cell of the array contains a 32-bit word, which is the color of a pixel. So now, you have to convert each color of this array into grayscale. But, before you modify any values in this array, you have to lock the surface with SDL_LockSurface(). When you are done, you have to unlock the surface with SDL_UnlockSurface().

To sum up, your function must:

  • Get the array of pixels.
  • Get the length of the array.
  • Lock the surface.
  • Convert each pixel into grayscale.
  • Unlock the surface.

This function must exit with an error message if any error occurs.

gcc   grayscale.o  `pkg-config --libs sdl2 SDL2_image` -o grayscale
$ ./grayscale image.png
